---
const title = "Container";
import { Code } from "astro:components";
import Layout from "../../../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout title={title}>
  <iframe
    src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}ui-examples/container/example.html`}
    style="width:100%; height: 300px; margin-bottom:10px;"></iframe>
  <a
    class="button"
    href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}ui-examples/container/example.html`}
    >View Example</a
  >
  <p>
    Having some sort of container class that you can reuse across your page
    helps ensure your rows and columns have consistent structure--it'll also
    save you from writing a lot of redundant styling! In this example, the class <code
      >.container</code
    > is used to center the content and set a maximum width.
  </p>

  <p>The gist of it is right here:</p>
  <Code
    code={`.container {
  display: flex;
  max-width: 1440px;
  margin: 0 auto;
}
`}
    lang="css"
  />
  <p>
    As you can see in the example, you can insert this within containers that
    run 100% width to help ensure your page content is aligned.
  </p>
</Layout>
